> ‘wet, moisten, water’.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Rennes in Brittany, France."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert Raymes was born about 1260, in Aydon, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert Raymes. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters."},"et":{"abt 1260–":"umbes 1260–Surnud","1258–Male":"1258–Surnud","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","–1323":"–1323","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1258":"1258","1323":"1323","abt 1260":"umbes 1260","1286":"1286","abt 1284":"umbes 1284","1284":"1284","abt 1286":"umbes 1286","1260":"1260","of Aydon, Northu, Engl":"Aydon, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt 1260–":"noin 1260–Kuollut","1258–Male":"1258–Kuollut","1284–Female":"1284–Kuollut","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","–1323":"–1323","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1258":"1258","1323":"1323","abt 1260":"noin 1260","1286":"1286","abt 1284":"noin 1284","1284":"1284","abt 1286":"noin 1286","1260":"1260","of Aydon, Nor